 For those confused about preban and why they are valuable. Here in the  state of Massachusetts  we have an assault weapons ban to contend with. title: For Sale:  7.62x51 (.308) TEAR GAS AMMUNITION - ISRAELI, Ultra-Rare
postcontent:
This may well be the rarest 7.62x51 military ammunition ever produced anywhere - period! 

Israeli Military manufactured ammo that features a dark gray tipped bullet loaded with a Tear Gas agent.  

Based on what I was able to find - this ammo was produced in extremely limited quantities for a few months back in 1961.  

It was  designed to be able to deliver a dose of tear gas at much greater ranges than the larger caliber gas launching guns of the day were capable of (typically limited to about 150 yards). 

The idea was to shoot at a hard surface near the intended target thereby releasing the Tear Gas agent. 

Ammo comes in it's original factory box and is in excellent (near perfect) condition.  

There are 20 rounds in the box that are loaded on four 5 round stripper clips.  

The ammo you see in the pictures is what you get. 

Primers are sealed with a purple color military sealer. 

This ammo is ever bit as deadly as any standard military ball round so it's not a novelty and must be treated with the same care as any live 7.62x51 ammunition. 

Price is $160 with pickup in the Brandon area. Shipping is available via UPS ground. Actual cost will be determined by your location. You must be at least 18 years old to purchase.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Pre 64 Winchester Model 12 Trench Gun:  what's in your bugout bag?
postcontent:
The mother of all home defense weapons, this Model 12 also boasts a few features not found on its more modern counterparts. 

First of all, yes ma'am, it will slam. Just like the Model 97 and the early Ithaca Model 37s, the Model 12 was never built with a trigger disconnect, so it is slam-fire capable.

Second, it is a true takedown weapon. The Winchester Model 12 breaks at the receiver, so the mag tube and the barrel come off together. The net effect is that the package breaks into two short, neat pieces:  the barrel/mag tube at 19 inches, and the buttstock and receiver at a little less. Both will fit neatly into your bugout bag. 

Which brings me to my final point.

This is a 1954 12-gauge, American-made pump-action shotgun, made of real walnut and blued steel. The only plastic in the whole damned gun is the buttplate, with Winchester proudly embossed in it. This isn't a Ruger 10/22 takedown. If you're serious enough to pack a bugout bag, you might as well put a serious weapon in it. 

Anyway, I'm interested in trades, plus or minus some cash. Specifically, a bolt gun; I have a warm spot for sporterized Mausers, especially 7x57 or 6.5mm. I also collect vintage Mossberg 22s and would gladly consider a Mossy 42m, 44, or 144LSB. Side by side doubles, especially old Ithacas or Fox Model Bs are welcome. Shoot me an offer; the worst I can say is no thank-you. If you've got nothing to trade, $400 cash would be acceptable, and you pay for the NICS. I have two FFLs kind enough to do them for the mandated $10.
